messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers

HTTP methods acceptable (based on code):
- All HTTP methods: No. Only POST and PUT are defined for this path in PriceTableController.
- HEAD: No. There is no HEAD mapping for this path, and no GET mapping exists for this endpoint to imply automatic HEAD handling.
- POST: Yes. addNewPaperItem is mapped to POST on this path.
- OPTIONS: No. There is no OPTIONS mapping defined for this path.
- TRACE: No. There is no TRACE mapping defined for this path.
- GET: No. There is no GET mapping defined for this path.
- PUT: Yes. editPaperItem is mapped to PUT on this path.
- DELETE: No. There is no DELETE mapping defined for this path.
- PATCH: No. There is no PATCH mapping defined for this path.

Explanation:
- The endpoint editPaperItem is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers", method = RequestMethod.PUT), meaning PUT is supported for this path.
- There is also another method, addNewPaperItem, annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers", method = RequestMethod.POST), so POST is also supported for this path.
- No methods for GET, DELETE, PATCH, HEAD, OPTIONS, or TRACE are defined for this path in this controller, so those methods are not considered acceptable from the code perspective.
- HEAD is not automatically inferred from PUT unless GET is available for the same path; since there is no GET mapping here, HEAD is not acceptable by code.
- The endpoint path correctly includes the path parameter {id} and begins with a forward slash, as required.
